Docker CI/CD Pipeline with CircleCI
Objectives
Design and implement a fully automated Docker image build, test, and push pipeline using CircleCI
Integrate container security scanning and multi-stage Docker builds into a CI/CD workflow
Configure environment-aware image tagging and conditional deployment logic in CircleCI
Prerequisites
Familiarity with Linux command-line operations on Ubuntu, including file editing and process management
Understanding of Git branching, commits, and remote repository operations
Conceptual knowledge of CI/CD pipelines, Docker image layering, and container lifecycle
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Required Toolchain
Requirement 1
Install Docker Engine, Git, Node.js 18, and the CircleCI CLI on the Ubuntu instance, then verify each tool responds correctly to a version query.

# Update package index
sudo apt-get update -y

# Install prerequisites for adding external repositories
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release

# Add Docker's official GPG key
sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

# Add Docker repository (single unbroken line written via printf)
printf 'deb [arch=%s signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu %s stable\n' \
  "$(dpkg --print-architecture)" \
  "$(lsb_release -cs)" \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list

# Official Docker install guide if the above URL changes:
# https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io

# Allow current user to run Docker without sudo
sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
newgrp docker
